[Q\&A with Matt Mochary](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1H3VAYMqnc3ks1-rWry-4TGT9V4t1mR39k98nKFCUK1A/edit)

I recently did a Q\&A via Zoom with a group of 20 CEOs for [The Great CEO Within](https://smile.amazon.com/Great-CEO-Within-Tactical-Building/dp/0578599287/ref=sr_1_1?crid=1MCCY7T07NTVQ&keywords=great+ceo+within&qid=1580502065&s=books&sprefix=great+ceo+%2Cstripbooks%2C209&sr=1-1) (several hours to read) and it was a lot of fun. I am excited to do more of these.

Here are my asks to do so:

- You gather a group of either
  - \>10 CEOs, or
  - \>40 members of the same company
- All of those people buy and read [The Great CEO Within (on Amazon)](https://smile.amazon.com/Great-CEO-Within-Tactical-Building/dp/0578599287/ref=sr_1_1?crid=1MCCY7T07NTVQ&keywords=great+ceo+within&qid=1580502065&s=books&sprefix=great+ceo+%2Cstripbooks%2C209&sr=1-1) or [The Great CEO Within (online)](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1ZJZbv4J6FZ8Dnb0JuMhJxTnwl-dwqx5xl0s65DE3wO8/edit).
  - If you are asking your employees to do so, please reimburse the cost to them
- All of those people post a review on Amazon with written comments
- Once I see those reviews on Amazon, we schedule a 50 minute Q\&A Zoom session
- You create a Google Doc that starts with the questions/answers below. Then ask all of the readers to put any additional questions they have for me in the doc.
- You share the doc with me \>1 week prior to the Q\&A. I will then answer as much in writing prior to the Q\&A as possible. That will leave the Q\&A time to process live issues in real-time, which is the most fun.
- 5 minutes prior to the end of the Q\&A session, I will ask all participants to type their feedback to me at the bottom of the doc

## If you have such a group, DM me.

### Examples of questions for Matt Mochary

- You mention if you’re not getting negative feedback, it’s not because there isn’t any, it’s just not being told to you. How do you suggest pulling it out of your team?
  - **Ask for it: Make sure your team understands that giving you negative feedback will not be punished, but cherished. It is important to explicitly say this to them, preferably in a one-on-one setting. When asking for feedback about himself as a manager, Lachy Groom, formerly of Stripe, asks “What feedback are you afraid to give because you think it will hurt my feelings? Please tell me that.” Even then, many people hesitate. I like to add, “Don’t tell me. Please just think it. Do you have it in your brain chamber? Yes? Now please tell me.”**
  - [**Feedback**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1wi714sobuQP72sKXw6J_gkwkhtVh1t6--op_Pk0YPxA/edit) **(15 min)**
- Where did the clearing conversational framework come from? ie. Thank them for the feedback. Repeat it back. Accept or reject?
  - **Pulled from various books like Radical Candor, Difficult Conversations, 15 Commitments of Conscious Leadership, etc. And then altered slightly as I used it over and over based on the feedback that I got.**
- Do you agree that there’s wartime and peacetime CEO’s?
  - **To me, its always wartime. The key is to act in curiosity and learning, not fear or anger. [Fear and Anger give bad advice](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1sDWHUm6zwEGiPBQH2Ig6DDvVL-IEQSlfNeQnR2mhjmE/edit) (3 min)**
- Can you explain the idea of making a bet with people who are in fear? How often? Direct reports or anyone?
  - **When I unpack an issue with one of my coachees (akin to a direct report), I always ask them to tell me what the problem is, tell me what they did to help create the issue, and then tell me steps they would advise me to take if I were in the exact same situation. This structure is usually enough for them to get out of their own blaming and victimhood, and see real steps that they can take to resolve the situation (often to just reverse what they did to help create it). But if they are still in fear, I simply make a bet with them. They predict that if they do X, then A will happen. I predict B will happen, which is the opposite of A. They then do X, and we see what happens. If they win the bet, they need never listen to me again. If I win the bet, then they have to listen to my guidance without pushback the next time I declare that they are in fear. I have made this bet hundreds of times. I have won every time. There’s no magic in it. I am simply not gripped by fear, as I am not in the situation myself.**
  - [**Fear and Anger give bad advice**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1sDWHUm6zwEGiPBQH2Ig6DDvVL-IEQSlfNeQnR2mhjmE/edit) **(3 min)**
- Are the full days of events always held on Mondays... or can you do them mid-week? What’re the pros/cons?
  - [**Calendar Cadence**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1vyxqhBB6GCCycPNvlaUyq1UcOLeCi7_nUdDIhHj1HQc/edit?usp=drive_web&ouid=102503928790226855337) **(3 min)**
  - **Any day of the week. Doesn’t matter. Usually best if each group picks a different day from the day in which the group leader must do her 1-1 and team meeting with her Manager.**
- How is a Chief of Staff different than a COO? Is there a natural progression after CSO for that hire? Or a place within the org that you should hire for that role from?
  - [**Chief of Staff**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1-tcubUwvktoV-Ou3bB6ynk2LLwNzdT3D_p_ILreyR_A/edit#) **(2 min)**
  - **The COS does not initially have direct reports. But the COS will quickly learn to think like the CEO. And if the COS is highly organized, then there is no reason that they cannot soon take on many reports and become the COO. If that is the case, though, they cease their COS role, and should hire their replacement as COS.**
  - **The natural place to hire this role from within the org is [Biz Ops](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1WidDWp5710YphCgkE-F6E0yunoaUP9iQKfKMT1EVGgA/edit#) (2 min), if you have that function. If you don’t yet have that function, cause your COS to create it.**
- In an interview, you mentioned that it’s best to start with small steps. ex: Firing someone at a lower level who isn’t performing to learn. Then taking baby steps. Do you have other examples of how to apply this as a CEO?
  - **This is just to prove that fear gives bad advice. If someone fully trusts me, then they start with a big one. It only takes 1-2 situations to prove to oneself that fear is giving me bad advice. Once proved, it applies to all situations.**
- What do the 3 sections of the google doc look like that you use for coaching? How are these meetings run?
  - [**1st 1-1 Meeting with Matt Mochary**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1vfZbW2GbL-q4gB97JcMH_P1nGRJKQ68LAOgNGbVV1qs/edit) **(5 min to read; 45 min to do)**
  - [**2nd (and beyond) 1-1 Meeting with Matt Mochary**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1TYNJjwzH_QxUbvoVSOjB__6gtvLKf8AAT3tqTKo3sO8/edit) **(2 min to read; 15 min to do)**
- What motivates you to coach? Is it the same reason that you’re helping previously incarcerated inmates find a job?
  - [**My Motivation**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/13slbLuJzDaribpTMdHfEuJpHsvQb2xI3PQCZR_fMB84/edit?usp=drive_web&ouid=102503928790226855337)
    - **I coach because I love getting to sit in the cockpit alongside the CEO. It gives me the illusion that I am helping to build the company.**
    - **I help x-cons because its so damn easy to do so. It gives me the illusion that I am saving lives.**
- He has a section on how to hire new senior leaders to replace existing young leaders. You frame it so the young leader can learn from an experienced person. But do I kick out the young leader from the leadership team meeting? I’d like to know more about the nuances of that.
  - **Unfortunately, yes, the Leadership Team meeting needs to be the fewest number of people who have reporting to them the whole company. There can be wider informational Team Leads meeting.**
    - [**Leadership vs Team Leads Meeting**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1OAdsheOc1RAS1-FC1PMImJ_sRGfug-SPamvTpu5P5vs/edit?usp=drive_web&ouid=102503928790226855337) **(3 min)**
  - **And while the above is a way to frame bringing on a more senior person, know that the fact that you needed to do so is a failure of your training. If you want a truly effective company, you will need to effectively train your team internally to be great managers. If you don’t, and you therefore have to constantly import managers, then you will end up with no consistency of management system, no deep trust among managers (because they will all be new), and little institutional knowledge among managers (again because they are all new).**
    - [**Hiring Execs: External vs Internal**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gaknANyT2UJC0YMF6zYnErMp4imlslDbPmg-d9yeGlI/edit) **(2 min)**
    - [**Teaching / Training**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1sGF4V0xFWjESabSZElwF3YienjtiLZtp81YTHe-zMpM/edit)
- He suggests in your leadership team meeting an exercise where everyone gives each other transparent feedback on each other written down on paper. I’d like to be led through that exercise in person.
  - **This takes a while ...**
- I’d also like him to unpack his way of helping employees resolve conflict with his google doc typing system.
  - [**Conflict Resolution**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1NzF-otDuBWKC2GShJKcFsxCyabK1V3skQwCMU89tDmY/edit) **(Deep Feedback)**
- Why and how does he use focusmate.com? How does it personally help him?
  - [**Accountability Partner**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1ljixCUhnIzKgNLzn5xzn-S1XEojM5Rblq3-83wiku28/edit) **(1 min)**
  - **I use it whenever I have open space in my workday calendar. For me, it provides the nudge that I need to get me to do the admin tasks that I want to get done. If I don’t schedule the Focusmate, I find that I end up playing online chess instead.**
- I can’t find a way to create KPIs and OKRs for the product and tech teams.It’s easy and effective to do for sales, marketing and customer success, a little more challenging for customer support, highly challenging for product and close to impossible for engineering. I’ve raised this issue many times and never got an answer that helped. What’s his take?
  - **Engineering doesn’t fit well with OKRs. Engineers want to produce, not be held to SLAs. I prefer to use the Product Roadmap to hold them accountable. Ask them to create a broad 12-month roadmap (with no dates), a more detailed 3-month roadmap with dates (a launch calendar), and a very detailed 2-week sprint plan. Hold them accountable to completing each sprint plan on the way to completing the 3-month roadmap. That 3-month roadmap is their OKR list.**
- Matt mentions that when finding a partner, “avoid one cardinal mistake: do not create a 50/50 partnership”. I have been avoiding bringing on my lifelong friend as my partner, because advice from peers has been that it will end in tears if we don’t have a 50/50 partnership (him being such a close friend). Can you talk to this cardinal mistake in the context of doing with trusted friends? Or is the idea of partnering with close friends a mistake in the first place?
  - **Being partners with a close friend is great. Having a 50/50 partnership with anyone is deadly, since there is no way to unblock a disagreement. And it doesn’t matter how small the disagreement is. Each and every decision requires unanimous agreement, otherwise by law you cannot move forward at all. If one decides to move forward anyway and continue to operate the business, they are in default of the operating agreement, and if the other sues, the other will win. And this happens regularly. That is what is deadly.**
- Do you have any advice on how to rank/choose which meetings to attend? Currently my staff and clients invite me to almost everything. And while there almost always is a valid reason for me to attend, it’s unsustainable and I am not optimally efficient with my time.
  - **First, stack rank them in terms of the value that they generate.**
  - **Then, think of all the things that you are NOT getting to on your priority list. That is your opportunity cost. Which meetings create MORE value than the top items on your priority list that you are not getting to. I would posit that is very few meetings.**
  - **Consider that if those meetings don’t create enough value for you, they don’t create enough value for anyone. What would make them more valuable generally?**
  - **And consider that the only thing IMHO that requires synchronous meetings are the final discussions around decisions and feedback. Everything else can be done asynchronously (and better): updates, initial phase of decision-making (here is the issue, here is my proposed solution, solicit the written comments from all involved).**
- Matt encourages positive reinforcement through compliments to the “losing team”. But how do I compliment a failing sales person when sales numbers are all they’re measured on, and those numbers are not being met?
  - **If someone is still at the company, there is something that you can praise. Once there is nothing left to praise, please [Fire Well (updated)](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1J3c8lGMzPJXMMSWNIh7UCsv-_4qKYZkrkwloIbu3BW8/edit) (5 min)**
- 1 hour per week for appreciation (follow ups and outreach) \- from “[How to become Insanely Well-Connected](https://firstround.com/review/how-to-become-insanely-well-connected/)” \- Matt: do you practice this, and if so, do you specifically carve out an actual hour per week and scroll through your rolodex? If so, has it been worth it, and if you have specific tips/practices for this, can you share it?
  - **Yes, yes, and yes. I send a text or WhatsApp message. Here’s an example from this past Friday:**
    - **![][image1]**
    - **Note that I mention something particular about the person (Angela and Tulum). This shows that I care enough to know and remember things about Brian as a human being.**
    - **As for success, well ... the people I coach could work with anyone on the planet.**
- “Trust dissipation is correlated with geographical distance…: \- How can we achieve the same level of trust we had pre-lockdown? According to the book, people trust immediate peers first, people they meet in person after that, and people they meet via video conference last (\!\!\!) \- how do we gain trust when video conference is all we have left for now?
  - **This is why [Agreement-Tracker: why you need one](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1QzGvP6MrmlD6YVilTiNjEsPgRRvjzvWrqGXKSz_c68k/edit) (3 min) is more important than ever.**
  - **And formalized informal time: [Do Remote Right](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1BY8fjKuF-NSQdMcw9SDwnYM1ZJLSW1bW7SNSzOHd-wU/edit) (work in progress)**
    - **Including gathering and remembering personal information about each other: [Trust and Like](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1BQOa7foLLxNXmGUhbvkzsvm0IVYOJZTFU4MKOmreCXc/edit?usp=drive_web&ouid=102503928790226855337) (5 min)**
    - **With an occasional vulnerable session at quarterly gatherings (even if they are remote): [Trust, Deep](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1IB7YDr_trYKavL_RdWTb8ddJt77eqDH_6H5BsK416FM/edit#) (2 min)**
  - **People also need to feel grounded on their own: [Remote happiness, how to create it](https://docs.google.com/document/d/19LLfA6TgDoynzduB-2Xp0XHmMN5lUiRxx8ht3VjYJ0E/edit) (9 min)**
- Chapter 9, Page 36: Alex Maccaw describes the CEO needing to leave the coding, if they want to run the company. How does this translate to Sales? Since Sales is my coding, and I’ve also heard the argument that the CEO should never stops selling.
  - **The key is to list all of the functions of the CEO. Then make sure that every function has a DRI (directly responsible individual). That DRI doesn’t have to be you. But whoever it is, must do the function fully. If you want to keep the function of high-impact sales, do so, as long as all of the other functions are covered well. And consider the only two functions that the CEO herself can do:**
    - **Create, update and write out the long-term vision for the company (getting buy-in of course). Then share it with all. (This is an ever-ongoing process.)**
    - **Be available to adjudicate conflict between departments and peers on the exec team. I recommend leaving at least 25% of the CEO’s calendar completely open so that she can resolve any conflict or blockage near-instantly.**
- Chapter 19 has spurred lots of my thinking regarding writing things down (documentation). Matt do you have any suggestions on how to formulate a culture (instead of tools) of documentation?
  - **I do the [AORs](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1v72Mozz6Zr-3Knzcd9yNcs1E8-QKk5NkTVmR6pIQj98/edit?usp=drive_web&ouid=102503928790226855337) (2 min) and use the [Processes Template](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1ky1BNH7f1xVa-hw7WOxI298a2nNP81OdORpbKdxLCj4/edit#gid=0).**
  - **Once a company does this once, the culture of documentation is created.**
  - **Another method is what Gitlab does.**
    - **All updates, issues, etc must be in writing, and be added to the company wiki to be reviewed. (ie- CEO will not review an issue that isn’t posted on the company wiki.) Therefore when the decision is made, there is nothing to push to the wiki. Its already there.**
- Any recommendations/thoughts on firing an employee with high mission alignment, but underperform? Shifting the employee to other roles to align skills may be interpreted by others as an excuse for underperformance.
  - **First read [Zone of Genius](https://docs.google.com/document/d/11UVWJox31Ani8Cq6Ymhm6DiVUiv5vPkOQd8ZdGpYmbs/edit#) (3 min)**
  - **Mission alignment is gold. You never want to lose someone who is committed. The next question then becomes “What do they love to do and are they great at?” Once you know that, put them in a role where they can do those things. Watch their performance skyrocket.**
  - **Shifting an employee to another role to align skills is not an excuse for underperformance. It is the way to create top performance.**
  - **If the person still doesn’t perform, then [Fire Well (updated)](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1J3c8lGMzPJXMMSWNIh7UCsv-_4qKYZkrkwloIbu3BW8/edit) (5 min)**
- How would you divide-and-conquer acquiring the knowledge in the book. Every one of the 30 chapters is incredible and valuable. Where would you start and finish on the different chapters if self-coaching from scratch?
  - **I would recommend getting organized as an individual first.**
  - **Then organizing the team, ie- communication flow between team members.**
  - **Only last would I attack individual departments.**
- What is it about your personality, mind and life path that allowed you to accumulate this specific knowledge and articulate it in this way? So many people say they want to build companies, make money and lead. So many people want to give advice about these things and in fact their jobs require them to do so. Almost none succeed or even really try sincerely. But you’ve actually gone and figured out the details of how to do so in a unique way. Why?
  - **This was generally my path: [Make Money, Have Fun, Do Good](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1P_8WALoefgBCQ9cR0Jgwztt_8-ppjJ1r7zpeyoikTa0/edit?folder=0B9tanFUuwmYSMHIyU2pkYTZSVkU)**
  - **The rest of the story is that I missed hanging out with my intellectual peers. So, I started to coach. Here is a bit on [My Motivation](https://docs.google.com/document/d/13slbLuJzDaribpTMdHfEuJpHsvQb2xI3PQCZR_fMB84/edit?usp=drive_web&ouid=102503928790226855337). The documentation of what seemed to work was simply getting sick of hearing my own voice repeating the same things over and over again, so I followed my own advice in [Writing vs Talking](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1bUiRJKbZUmiFK2aWbYQtogxqrnygwFYwkLXwtnkyjFM/edit?usp=drive_web&ouid=102503928790226855337) (3 min).**
  - **On the book, I wasn’t even going to publish it. Credit for that goes to Alex MacCaw of Clearbit. He was the one that assembled all of my material and pushed it out the door.**
- What area of management capability / skill (i.e. pick a chapter in GCW) are CEOs in your experience most deluded about? What do they think they’re ok at but actually harming themselves with bad behavior? I ask this question because there is an enormous amount to do and I would like to tune my own sense of what I need to work on first.
  - **Most never really create an environment that welcomes and elicits true [Feedback](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1wi714sobuQP72sKXw6J_gkwkhtVh1t6--op_Pk0YPxA/edit) (15 min). Brian Armstrong is likely best at this. He LOVES hard feedback. Never ever gets angry. And really acts on the feedback. Still, new people feel fear, and it takes a long time (and often my direct involvement) to get them to give real feedback.**
  - **Writing down the ongoing Vision for the company and sharing it with all in a way that connects each person’s role to that Vision.**
  - **Implementing a company-wide [Agreement-Tracker: why you need one](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1QzGvP6MrmlD6YVilTiNjEsPgRRvjzvWrqGXKSz_c68k/edit) (3 min)**
    - **Those are the three biggest ongoing delusions (or omissions) that I see.**
- The personal habits at the front of the book are gold. Is it the CEO’s job to instil these habits in execs if they don’t already exist?
  - **Yes. Or at least ask each exec if these are habits that they want to adopt and be held accountable to. Ask habit by habit so that they can say yes to some, and no to others. Then help them implement the ones that they want to adopt.**
  - **Here is an example of how to do that in your next 1-1 with each person**
    - _Please read [On Time](https://docs.google.com/document/d/16QP9shWuJbHQYwqU4Fo7YAXzakzcBx2LTyQgc6oSgfw/edit?usp=drive_web&ouid=102503928790226855337). It takes about 3 minutes to read. Is this a habit that you want me to hold you accountable to: Yes or No? write here (It is OK to say no.)_
    - _Please read [Top Goal (CEO)](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1rWlx4P0Kpp4E8nFajcwDa4or_1EINv_ITTM-Ruo5XvQ/edit?usp=drive_web&ouid=102503928790226855337). It takes about 3 minutes to read. Is this a habit that you want me to hold you accountable to: Yes or No? write here (It is OK to say no.)_
- Is it appropriate for the CEO to coach his exec team using for example your 1-1 coaching templates? Or is coaching of the exec team in this way not the CEOs job?
  - **It is TOTALLY APPROPRIATE. I want every CEO to copy and paste my methodology. When I coach a CEO, I first show them my methodology, which usually takes 4 meetings to fully grok. At Meeting \#4, if the CEO is feeling more engaged, empowered, successful, etc, then I ask them to use the same methodology with their reports.**
- How do you find a great CEO coach? I am interested both in specific networks and individuals and in what to look for (qualities, experience, approach) when picking a CEO coach
  - **Here are my best [coach recommendations](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1NwZ3B7cqk15Ieecpofrto5_GBH0LaadabmrYAaRmtak/edit). Prismaticco, in particular, has done a great job of finding matches for people. I have received consistently great feedback from people that I have sent in their direction.**
  - **Also [Coach \- how to find one](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1P3xgXHzXqjoytTDRyZbXcWc8GKDGhCHfRIHiN9lVGkA/edit) (2 min)**
- Why is management skill so neglected and so understudied? Your book is incredible and I believe that it addresses many of the primary barriers to building a massive business. So why do so few people try to get good at management despite the obvious rewards? And why is the median management training so poor e.g. the average MBA would fail 90% of the items in the book. I ask this to (1) try cement my own understanding and really try grok why I should be focusing on building genuine CEO skill and (2) to figure out how to persuade my team to focus on their management capacity
  - **There is actually a lot of great management training out there. Unfortunately, its not found in schools. Its found in companies: Google, Facebook, Apple, Amazon, etc. But I think that is true for many areas of business learning. The best training is in the companies themselves.**
- How important are peer networks in cementing the lessons and sustaining the journey of learning to be a capable CEO? Any particular networks you like and recommend?
  - **Peer networks are phenomenal group therapy. They let you know that you’re not alone, and force you to focus on the hard important things, rather than the easy unimportant things.**
  - **10x CEO, Vistage, YPO are all good. There are many others, and likely they are good as well. I have never heard of a bad peer network. There are too many good ones for a bad one to survive.**
- What is your best advice on building candor into company culture? You mention a great process in the book for resolving issues, etc that help remove emotion but that requires triggers. How can one preempt this?
  - **Great question. Let’s answer this during the Q\&A.**
- How does one prevent the wiki from getting too large and outdated? In the same way that one has to consider code maintenance, does one not have to consider wiki maintenance?
  - **Yes. The solution is the same as code maintenance. There needs to be regular clean-up of Wiki debt.**
- Deploying RAPID. What’s the best way to start? Just go _Cold Turkey_? Also, is there value in doing this from a startup phase? I.e team of 2?
  - **This technique is really meant for bigger (or remote) orgs. With smaller teams that are in constant communication, the overhead of a RAPID is likely not justified.**
  - **To implement, first share the readings with the team. Ask them if they want to experiment with it. Then you write up the first one, and toddle through it. Remember to ask for feedback at the end of each one as to how it could have gone better. Do that until you have a process that all are bought into.**
- Some of the OKR material I’ve one though notes that one should go for goals that you’re only 50/50 confident you can make to prevent sandbagging. This doesn’t gel very well with Impeccable Agreements. Is it supposed to? Or is the latter only meant to refer to your tasks on Asana for instance?
  - **Goals that are only likely to be achieved 70% is what Google has found to create optimal effort. But its a bit more challenging to track.**
  - **Impeccable Agreements do not apply to OKRs. They apply primarily to tasks in Asana, meeting start times, etc. The tactical actions.**
